AGI - Stop for thirty days to attacks on power stations and Ukrainian civil infrastructures>. Afterwards, there will be a ceasefire to arrive at a "permanent peace" which will, however, warn Moscow, have as a key condition the interruption of all military aid in Kiev. The one-and-a-half-hour call between the President of the United States, Donald Trump, and the Russian one, Vladimir Putin, has produced a turning point in the conflict between Russia and Ukraine, of which however the reach will be understood after the reaction of Kiev.
"The leaders - the White House has explained in an account of the call - have agreed that the path towards peace will begin with a ceasefire energy and infrastructural, as well as with technical negotiations on the implementation of a ceasefire marine in the Black Sea, a ceasefire complete and a permanent peace". During the interview Trump and Putin agreed that a better "bilateral relationship" between the US and Russia will help global economic growth and geopolitical stability, with "enormous economic agreements» on the horizon. The two leaders then sent a message to Iran on nuclear power: "It should never be in the position to destroy Israel."
The warning is also a clear indication: the two countries will address the issue of the proliferation of strategic weapons, but it is not clear how far this commitment can go.
Negotiations in Saudi Arabia will continue and will have to give further answers in a short time. Putin, to confirm the value of the call, ordered the army to suspend attacks on Ukrainian energy infrastructure. The Russian president, according to what the Kremlin said, however, asked the "complete termination" of weapons supplies in Kiev and the sharing of intelligence information. The Russian President also informed Trump of an exchange of 175 prisoners >for part with Ukraine and should be completed tomorrow.
At the moment it is unclear whether Ukraine will respond to the White House and Kremlin statements. Ukrainian president, Volodymyr Zelensky, had told the United States to be favorable to a ceasefire of thirty days but without the conditions asked by Putin, that the White House did not mention in his report. Meanwhile, from Berlin, the outgoing German Chancellor, Olaf Scholz, and the French President, Emmanuel Macron, promised that they will continue with military support in Kiev.
The will of Washington and Moscow to leave Europe away from the table is, however, explicit in the passage of the report of the Kremlin in which it is read that the two countries agree on the need to carry out the negotiation in a "bilateral" way with the appointment of expert groups > of both nations.<br> &nbsp;
