AGI - The call between Russian and American presidents, Vladimir Putin and Donald Trump, is ongoing, to discuss a possible peace agreement between Russia and Ukraine.>&nbsp; The call - said the spokesman of the Kremlin, Dmitri Peskov >- is&nbsp; it was organized according to a mutual agreement. "This is a mutual agreement," he said to journalists, when asked at the initiative of those who had organized the interview. Peskov<b> </b> has also announced that Putin and Trump will discuss not only of Ukraine but also of the normalization of bilateral relations:&nbsp;"There is also a large number of issues on the further normalization of our bilateral relations, on the solution of the Ukrainian question. All this must be discussed by the two presidents."
Yesterday the White House spokesman, Karolin Leavitt>, said that he was close to a peace agreement. Putin expressed doubts about how a ceasefire would be implemented, while Trump reiterated the will to end the war.
Ukrainian president Volodymyr Zelensky, > for his part, accepted the idea of a partial truce, but European allies criticize the leader of the Kremlin because it does not immediately stop the fighting. Moscow seems to want to extend the negotiations, believing that it is in advantage on the military level. The sale of territories and the recognition of Crimea are among the most delicate issues. Putin aims at a new security architecture in Europe, establishing a red line for the expansion of NATO.&nbsp;&nbsp;>
<h2>Kiev, we want the end of the war by the year
Ukraine wants a ceasefire "without conditions", but is ready to resist the enemy and believes that this year it can end the war on a large scale. It was declared by the Foreign Ministry, Andriy Sybiha>, as reported by Rbk Ukraine. Commenting on a possible ceasefire of 30 days, Sybiha said that Ukraine is "ready to resist" if the Russian Federation will not accept the proposal on the table. In particular, he added that Kiev believed in the end of the war on a large scale in 2025 and defined a possible truce as "a great step forward" towards peace. "We believe the war will end this year, we really want it to end this year. We are all united by this strategic goal: to reach a just, complete and lasting peace," said the minister. "Ukraine supports the United States proposal for a temporary ceasefire. We are waiting for Russia's response," he concluded, "this will be a huge step forward to approach peace." &nbsp;
<h2>Nyt, fears that Trump accepts the sale of Odessa to Putin</h2>
The president of the United States, Donald Trump, could accept to cede the port of Odessa to Russia. According to the New York Times citing conversations with the collaborators of Ukrainian President Zelensky, dating back to February, Kiev is concerned that Trump can satisfy "other wishes of Putin" regarding other territories, including, perhaps, Odessa and its port. The New York Times did not specify what these concerns were based on.
At the same time, the New York Times recalls that Trump's collaborators have clarified that Russia "will surely remain Crimea", annexed in 2014, and also "strongly let it be understood that it will get almost all the territory in its possession", or about 20% of the Ukrainian territory. The Special Envoy Usa Steve Witkoff, who had talks with Vladimir Putin in Moscow on March 13, said that the two parties discussed a possible agreement on "access to ports" in the Black Sea. According to the American president, in the phone call with Putin we will talk about "terre and power plants" (probable reference to the nuclear power plant of Zaporizhzhia, under Russian control). Trump noted that "many elements" of a peace agreement on Ukraine have already been agreed, "but much remains to be done."&nbsp;
